snippet.textDisplay:
"The future is not set."

Terminator 3: Judgment Day is inevitable.

Terminator Salvation: Judgment Day already happened.

Terminator Genisys: Skynet's existence is inevitable, coming from the Skynet's mouth itself.

Dark Fate: We stopped Judgment Day...except not really. Skynet is gone...only it isn't.

"There is no fate but what we make for ourselves."

Terminator 3: JUDGMENT DAY. IS. INEVITABLE.

Salvation: who cares what anyone did in that thing?

Genisys: You are nothing but a relic from a deleted timeline -- the whole movie in a nutshell.

Dark Fate: opens up by killing John Connor -- what more evidence do you need that nothing anyone does in these movies matters?

For a franchise whose main theme is defying fate and that the future can be changed, it has consistently subsisted on sequels that have ignored and outright defied its entire premise.

They shoild change it to:
"The future IS set because history keeps repeating itself. There is no fate but that which a bunch of hack writers make for our worthless lives."

Some movies just weren't meant to be franchised, like Highlander.

snippet.textDisplay:
I get the distinct impression that the production of this movie involved a ton of back-slapping over how they were doing right everything the other post-T2 movies did wrong. And yet it looks just as exceedingly mediocre. Whattyaknow?

P.S. Hollywood still doesn't seem to realize that an awful lot of what made T1 and T2 successful (and still highly enjoyable) was their lack of access to CGI. Virtually every single action piece looks real because it basically was real, and even if the action is less plentiful or extreme that reality brings a minor horror element to the proceedings that gets audiences excited. Heck, while we're at it, even the fake Arnold in the T1 scene when he does self-surgery on his face actually works great, because the artificial (but grounded in the physical world) look adds to the horror. And the T-1000 was either an actual person or an otherworldly metal blob at all times, avoiding the uncanny valley issues of CGI that isn't careful constructed.
